  "local_port": 55644,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I get my songs converted to karaoke or instrumental?",
  "response": "Converting your songs to karaoke or instrumental versions can be done in several ways, depending on your technical skills, budget, and the tools you have access to. Here's a step-by-step guide:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Use Online Karaoke/Instrumental Conversion Tools**\nThere are AI-powered tools and websites that can strip vocals from songs or create karaoke/instrumental versions. Some popular options include:\n- **Moises**: Separates vocals, instruments, and drums using AI. You can remove the vocals to create an instrumental track.\n- **LALAL.AI**: Another AI-based tool that removes vocals or specific instruments.\n- **Vocal Remover**: A free web-based tool that removes vocals from songs.\n\n**Steps**:\n1. Upload your song to the platform.\n2. Select the option to remove vocals or isolate instruments.\n3. Download the resulting instrumental track.\n\n---\n\n### **2. Use Audio Editing Software**\nIf you're comfortable with audio editing, software like **Audacity** (free) or **Adobe Audition** (paid) can help you create instrumental or karaoke versions.\n\n**Steps**:\n1. Open the song in the software.\n2. Use the *Vocal Reduction and Isolation* effect in Audacity to remove vocals (this may not be perfect).\n3. Export the edited track as an instrumental.\n\n---\n\n### **3. Hire a Professional**\nFor high-quality results, consider hiring a music producer or audio engineer to create karaoke or instrumental versions. They can use advanced tools and techniques to isolate or recreate tracks.\n\n**Where to Find Professionals**:\n- Freelance platforms like **Fiverr**, **Upwork**, or **SoundBetter**.\n- Local music studios or producers.\n\n---\n\n### **4. Use Karaoke Software**\nSome software is specifically designed for creating karaoke tracks, such as:\n- **Karaoke Builder Studio**: Allows you to create karaoke versions by removing vocals and syncing lyrics.\n- **Vanbasco Karaoke Player**: Can play MIDI files, which you can create from your songs using MIDI conversion tools.\n\n---\n\n### **5. Recreate the Instrumental Track**\nIf you have access to the original stems (individual tracks for vocals, drums, bass, etc.), you can mute the vocal track and export the rest as an instrumental. Alternatively, you can:\n- Recreate the instrumental using MIDI or virtual instruments in a Digital Audio Workstation (DAW) like **FL Studio**, **Logic Pro**, or **Ableton Live**.\n\n---\n\n### **6. License Karaoke Versions**\nIf your song is a cover or a popular track, you can purchase pre-made karaoke versions from platforms like:\n- **Karaoke Version**\n- **Sing King Karaoke**\n- **Sunfly Karaoke**\n\n---\n\n### **Tips for Better Results**\n- Start with high-quality audio files (e.g., WAV or FLAC) for better separation.\n- Be aware that vocal removal tools may leave artifacts or not work perfectly with complex mixes.\n- For commercial use, ensure you have the rights to create karaoke versions of the song.\n\nLet me know if you'd like more details on any of these methods! \ud83c\udfb6",
  "temperature": 1.0,
